[The reported number of new cases of tuberculosis (TB) decreased from 11 171 in 2010 to 10 528 in 2011. Despite the overall decline in tuberculosis (TB) incidence in the United States to these record low numbers, outbreaks of TB in congregate settings such as among homeless persons in shelters or jails continue to challenge TB control efforts (1-4). In the United States, 1 percent of the population experiences homelessness in a given year, but 5.8 percent of persons with TB reported being homeless within the previous year (1). The homeless are frequently substance abusers (i.e., alcohol or illicit substances), have HIV infection, temporarily reside in crowded shelters or jails, and often lack ready access to the medical care, all conditions that increase the risk of TB.

Genotyping of patient TB isolates has become a helpful tool to establish transmission pathways. Patients who have the same genotype are assumed to be infected with the same strain and are part of a genotype cluster. Genotyping, when combined with epidemiologic data, can then help identify unsuspected settings in which TB transmission has occurred, such as exposure to an unsuspected patient with active pulmonary TB in a congregate setting, e.g., a homeless shelter, mental health facility, or jail. Through the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention National Tuberculosis Genotyping Service, local health departments in the United States are able to submit for genotyping one _Mycobacterium tuberculosis_ isolate from each culture-confirmed TB case within their jurisdiction (http://www.cdc.gov/tb/publications/factsheets/statistics/genotyping.htm).

As stated in moderator ML's comments in a prior ProMED-mail post (Tuberculosis - USA: (FL) fatal, homeless shelter 20120710.1196037): Every active pulmonary TB case is a potential outbreak. TB control requires political will to commit adequate financial resources for early detection of cases of active tuberculosis and its prompt and complete treatment, accompanied by identification and treatment of active and latent TB infection among contacts. In the late 1980s and early 1990s, the United States saw a resurgence of TB as funding fell for TB control activities. This was reversed by commitment on a national level of adequate resources. Cutting TB control activities is bad health policy that will foster the potential for this contagious infection to spread throughout the community. The inevitable result of less detection and effective treatment for TB is more disease in the future, as well as costly drug resistance.

1. CDC. Features: Homelessness is a risk factor for TB. Available at: http://www.cdc.gov/features/dsTB2011Data/.
2. CDC. Tuberculosis outbreak among homeless persons--King County, Washington, 2002-2003. MMWR 2003;52:1209-10. Available at: http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5249a4.htm
3. CDC. Tuberculosis outbreak associated with a homeless shelter--Kane County, Illinois, 2007-2011. MMWR 2012;61:186-9. Available at: http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6111a3.htm
4. CDC. Notes from the Field: Tuberculosis Cluster Associated with Homelessness -- Duval County, Florida, 2004-2012. MMWR 2012:61(28);539-540. Available at:
http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6128a5.htm
